 <head >
 <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Isocrates</name>
 </head>
 <p >Born <date  when='-0436'>436 BCE</date>, died <date  when='-0338'>338 BCE</date> (source
 for date: <bibl  n='OCD3'>
 <title >OCD</title>
 <edition >3</edition>
 </bibl>). <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Isocrates</name> was the child of a wealthy
 flute-manufacturer who gave him an excellent education. He is said to have studied under
 <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Prodicus</name>, <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Gorgias</name>,
 <name  type='person'>Tisias</name>, <name  type='person'>Theramenes</name>, and <name  type='person'>Socrates</name>. <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Isocrates</name> spent the
 decade of the <date  from='-0399' to='-0390'>390s</date> writing speeches. However, much of
 the rest of <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Isocrates</name>’ life was dedicated to
 teaching; he established a school at <placeName  key='Athens'>Athens</placeName> sometime
 before <date  when='-0386'>386 BCE</date> (source for date: <bibl  n='OCD3'>
 <title >OCD</title>
 <edition >3</edition>
 </bibl>). Among his students were the orators <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Hyperides</name>
 and <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Isaeus</name>, the historians <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Ephorus</name> and <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Theopompus</name>, and the atthidographer
 <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Androtion</name>. <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Isocrates</name>’ works are characterised by expressions of great love of
 <placeName  key='Athens'>Athens</placeName> and by the promotion of ideas of
 Panhellenism, whereby, in his view, all of the Greek peoples could unite and declare war
 on the barbarous Persians. Of his works, twenty-one discourses on a wide range of topics
 and nine letters survive, most of which are considered to be genuine. (See also the genre
 of <name  n='oratory' type='ancientGenre'>Oratory</name>.)</p>
 <byline >Christopher Cotten</byline>
